    { type: "paragraph", text: "Section 106 agreements for major residential schemes increasingly include viability review mechanisms (VRMs) — clauses that allow local planning authorities to revisit the affordable housing contribution if a scheme's outturn performance exceeds the assumptions in the original viability appraisal. For an Assistant Development Manager at Latimer, understanding these mechanisms is essential: they directly affect development appraisal cash flows, grant funding drawdown strategy, and the quantum of affordable housing your organisation delivers. Unlike a speculative housebuilder trying to minimise affordable housing, an RP-led scheme must navigate the tension between maximising affordable output, satisfying Homes England conditions, and managing the commercial viability of cross-subsidy models." },
    { type: "heading", text: "What Are Viability Review Mechanisms?" },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "VRMs are contractual provisions embedded in S106 agreements that enable an LPA to reassess scheme viability at predetermined trigger points — typically pre-implementation, mid-point, and/or near-completion. The London Plan (2021) Policy H5 and the Mayor's Affordable Housing and Viability SPG established the 'Fast Track' and 'Viability Tested' routes. Under the Viability Tested Route, early, mid, and late-stage reviews are standard. Outside London, many LPAs have adopted similar approaches following the 2019 revised NPPF and PPG on viability. The mechanism typically compares the developer's actual or projected costs and revenues against the original Financial Viability Assessment (FVA), calculating any 'surplus' to be shared — usually 60% to the LPA (as additional affordable housing or commuted sum) and 40% to the developer." },
    { type: "key_term", term: "Viability Review Mechanism (VRM)", text: "A contractual clause in a S106 agreement that permits reassessment of a development's financial viability at specified trigger points, potentially requiring additional affordable housing or commuted payments if the scheme performs better than originally appraised." },
    { type: "key_term", term: "Overage / Clawback Clause", text: "A specific type of VRM provision requiring the developer to share 'super-profits' — revenues exceeding original assumptions — with the LPA, typically as additional affordable housing units or a financial contribution. The surplus share split is commonly 60:40 (LPA:developer) but varies by authority." },
    { type: "heading", text: "Why This Matters Differently for Housing Associations" },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "For Latimer/Clarion, the dynamics of VRMs differ markedly from a private housebuilder. First, where Latimer is delivering a mixed-tenure scheme with a cross-subsidy model (market sale units funding affordable housing), an overage clause could theoretically capture improved market sale revenues — but the 'surplus' may already be earmarked for additional affordable units or used to reduce grant dependency. Second, Homes England Affordable Homes Programme (AHP) grant conditions require delivery of a specified number and tenure of affordable homes. If a VRM triggers additional affordable housing beyond grant-funded units, the RP must determine whether these additional units attract further grant or must be absorbed within scheme viability. Third, the RP's own board-approved hurdle rate and internal rate of return (IRR) thresholds interact with VRM exposure — an overage clause that claws back surplus above, say, a 12% developer return can compress the RP's already-thin margin on cross-subsidised schemes." },
    { type: "callout", label: "APC Tip — Worked Example", text: "Scenario: Latimer is delivering a 200-unit scheme in an Outer London borough — 65% affordable (funded via AHP grant + cross-subsidy from 70 market sale units), policy-compliant at 35% but Latimer is voluntarily delivering more. The original FVA assumed GDV of £42m for market sale units. At late-stage review, actual sales indicate GDV of £46m — a £4m surplus. Under the S106 VRM, 60% (£2.4m) is payable to the LPA. However, Latimer can argue: (a) the surplus is already recycled into above-policy affordable delivery; (b) the additional affordable units carry their own costs not in the original FVA; (c) Homes England conditions cap the RP's profit to 6% on affordable tenure. The negotiation strategy should focus on demonstrating that the 'surplus' is already hypothecated to social value delivery, potentially converting the overage into in-kind affordable units rather than a commuted sum — which aligns with the RP's mission and avoids cash outflow." },
    { type: "heading", text: "Trigger Points and Practical Management" },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "Early-stage (pre-implementation) reviews are triggered if a scheme is not substantially commenced within a specified period (commonly 2 years from permission). This is particularly relevant for RP-led phased schemes where Homes England funding milestones may not align with LPA commencement expectations. Mid-point reviews occur when a specified percentage of units (often 50-75%) are sold or occupied. Late-stage reviews happen when 75-90% of market units are sold. Each review typically requires submission of an updated FVA using outturn data — actual construction costs, sales values achieved, and finance costs incurred. The S106 will define the 'benchmark land value' (BLV) and 'target developer return' against which surplus is measured." },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "As an ADM at Latimer, you should ensure the original S106 drafting protects the RP's position. Key negotiation points include: (i) ensuring the BLV is agreed as a fixed figure (not subject to review upward); (ii) defining 'developer return' to reflect the blended return appropriate for an RP (6% on affordable, 15-20% on market sale) rather than a flat 15-20% on total GDV; (iii) capping any overage payment so it cannot exceed the cost of delivering additional affordable units at the defined tenure mix; (iv) ensuring grant funding received is treated as a revenue item (reducing surplus) rather than excluded from the calculation; and (v) building in a 'priority return' mechanism so the RP recovers its overheads and risk margin before any surplus is calculated." },
    { type: "key_term", term: "Benchmark Land Value (BLV)", text: "The land value adopted in the original FVA as the threshold below which the scheme is deemed unviable. Typically derived from Existing Use Value (EUV) plus a landowner premium (commonly 10-30%). In RP-led schemes on public sector land, BLV may be set at a nominal level or linked to a transfer price agreed with Homes England or the GLA." },
    { type: "heading", text: "Interaction with Homes England AHP Grant Conditions" },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "Homes England's Capital Funding Guide (CFG) sets out requirements for grant-funded schemes. A critical issue arises where a VRM triggers additional affordable housing: does Homes England treat this as a 'bonus' output (improving the programme's additionality) or as evidence that the original grant quantum was excessive (triggering potential grant clawback)? In practice, Homes England generally welcomes additional affordable units, but the RP must ensure that: (a) the additional units are reported correctly in IMS (Investment Management System); (b) the grant rate per unit remains within scheme cost benchmarks; and (c) the RP is not inadvertently creating a cross-subsidy surplus that Homes England could argue should have reduced the original grant bid. This requires careful modelling at appraisal stage — building in sensitivity analysis for VRM scenarios so the grant funding application is robust." },
    { type: "callout", label: "APC Tip — Examiner Angle", text: "An assessor may ask: 'How would you advise your organisation on the risks of a late-stage viability review on a grant-funded mixed-tenure scheme?' A strong Level 3 answer would demonstrate: (1) understanding that VRMs are standard in policy terms and cannot simply be resisted; (2) practical steps taken at S106 negotiation stage to protect the RP's position (blended return, BLV fixing, grant treatment); (3) ongoing monitoring of actual vs appraised performance to prepare for reviews; (4) liaison with Homes England where additional units may arise; and (5) awareness that commuted sums may be less desirable than in-kind units for an RP because they represent cash outflow without asset creation." },
    { type: "heading", text: "Deferred Contributions and Phased Delivery" },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "Some S106 agreements include deferred affordable housing contribution mechanisms — where the full policy-compliant quantum is not deliverable at planning stage (due to viability), but the LPA secures a mechanism for future 'catch-up'. For RP-led schemes, this can be advantageous: Latimer might secure permission for a first phase with 25% affordable (below the 35% policy) with a deferred contribution mechanism that, upon review, could increase the percentage in later phases. This approach allows the RP to manage cash flow and grant drawdown across phases while demonstrating to the LPA a genuine commitment to maximising affordable output. The key risk is that market conditions deteriorate, the deferred review shows no surplus, and the LPA is left with below-policy provision — a political and reputational risk for the RP as much as the LPA." },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "In drafting deferred contribution clauses, ensure the S106 specifies: the review methodology (open-book vs. formulaic); the inputs to be updated (construction costs indexed to BCIS, sales values to Land Registry HPIs); the dispute resolution mechanism (typically an independent surveyor appointed jointly or by RICS President); and a longstop date after which no further review can be triggered. For Latimer, it is also important that the deferred mechanism does not conflict with Homes England's milestone requirements — if grant is predicated on delivering X affordable units by a certain date, a deferred S106 mechanism that pushes delivery later could jeopardise funding." },
    { type: "heading", text: "RICS Professional Standards and Ethical Obligations" },
    { type: "paragraph", text: "RICS members advising on viability (including preparing or reviewing FVAs for VRM purposes) must comply with the RICS Professional Statement 'Financial viability in planning: conduct and reporting' (effective 2019, updated 2021). This requires transparency, objectivity, and a standardised approach to inputs. As an APC candidate, you should be able to reference this standard and explain how it applies to your role — even if you are instructing external consultants to prepare the FVA, you have a professional duty to ensure the work is compliant and that you understand the methodology sufficiently to challenge it. In the RP context, there is an ethical dimension: Latimer's mission is to deliver affordable homes, so 'gaming' a VRM to minimise affordable output would be inconsistent with the organisation's charitable objectives and RICS ethical standards (Rule 1: Act with integrity)." }
